Species overview

Pinocchio’s dolphin (Delfinus mendax) is a long-lived endangered dolphin with age-selective sampling due to a positive relationship between snout length and age. There are multiple sub-populations, including one in Acme Archipelago which used to have high bycatch in commercial fisheries until about 20 years ago. Since then, management measures have reduced bycatch rates and managers think the population might be recovering.

Biologists have been collecting demographic and genetic data for Pinocchio’s dolphin from fishery samples for about 10 years. Reproductive output is independent of age, and of 1 offspring per year, such that population dynamics can be described as:

\[ N_t = N_0 e^\lambda \]

(Population numbers are low at the moment, so we can assume exponential growth).

From previous studies, we also know age-at-maturity to be exactly 5. Age is measured exactly from teeth and validating procedures have confirmed that age estimation is 100% accurate (!!).

There are 9600 invidivual samples (juveniles and adults) for which sex has been recorded (Sex, females only) and age estimated (A, from dental records).

nrow(samp_delfi_A$Samps)
[1] 9600

The sampling year in Samps is recorded in column Y and goes from Year 25 to Year 30.

The first column (Me) is a unique identifier for each individual consisting of four words—the first and fourth are unique to the individual and the second and third are the first component of the individual’s mother and father, respectively. So, you can use them to find (or verify) parent-offspring pairs.

NB: you’ll be reassured to know—I was—that Mark didn’t come up with an infinite list of weird syllabled words for the purpose of simulating pedigree—each word is called a proquint and designed to be a pronounceable unique identifier, see more here.

Before we have a look at the samples, we’ll first create two columns poss_par and poss_off as booleans to identify each record as a potential “parent” or “offspring”. Since age-at-maturity is strictly 5, we can classify all individuals of age 4 or less as possible offsprings, and individuals of age 5 or more as possible parents.

samp_delfi_A$Samps$poss_off <- samp_delfi_A$Samps$A < agemat
samp_delfi_A$Samps$poss_par <- samp_delfi_A$Samps$A >= agemat

From there, we can look at the number of adults and offsprings that were sampled for each sampling year by adult age:

Framework

Our end goal is to estimate population size per year, \(N_y\), for Pinocchio’s dolphin. As we are only including female samples, we are focusing on female population dynamics.

We do this by maximising the likelihood of the observed parent-offspring-pairs given our population dynamics model and what we know about our samples (e.g., the year the juveniles were born in, the number of samples, etc.). Since the population abundance directly scales with the probability of observing an Parent-Offspring-Pair, we can work backwards from the estimated probability of \(Pr(POPs|N_0, \lambda)\) to gain an estimate of \(N_y\) (with a few assumptions…!).

The steps in the modelling framework that are relevant to Pinocchio’s dolphin in the Acme Archipelago are:

  • Unpack model parameters
  • Predict population dynamics given parameters
  • Compute expected probability of a POP
  • Return the likelihood of the observed number of POPs

Since age is measured with 100% accuracy in our population of interest, we do not need to also compute the expected probability of a POP given uncertainty about sample covariates.

(NB: if we want to be precise, the POPs are actually MOPs, or even, MDPs—Mother-Daughter-Pairs. But we’ll keep calling them POPs below.)

Data preparation

We first summarise the sampling data in order to generate the objects we need to compute the expected number of POPs in our dataset. Eventually, we will end up computing the probability, for each possible parent \(j\), that they are the parent of an offspring \(i\), given what we know about them (“the covariates”). For now, we start by exploring our samples in order to understand how the dataset gets broken down to generate quantities of interest for CKMR.

Let’s go back to our probability of observing a POP. In order to be a possible parent to a given juvenile, you need, at the very least:

  • to have still been alive when the juvenile was born
  • to have been mature when the juvenile was born

The first item is given to us by the year of sampling. Since samples for Pinocchio’s dolphin come from dead bycaught individuals in the fishery, an adult cannot be the parent of a juvenile born in a year after it was sampled. The second item can be derived from the age of the adult at sampling, as that will give us the birth year, and, if we know age-at-maturity (as we do here), the year at which the adult started contributing to the offspring pool.

NB: For Pinocchio’s dolphin maturity is knife-edge at age 5, which simplifies things greatly. Normally, the switch to maturity would be spread over a few years.

The adult dataset can be re-arranged to better show the distribution of these key quantities (adult age, birth and maturity years) and how they are distributed in our dataset:

Code 
samp_delfi_A$Samps$B <- with(samp_delfi_A$Samps, Y - A) # add birth year B

So, most of the adults in our dataset became mature between years 25 and 30, and were sampled the year they became mature. In this example, fishing happened after the reproductive season, so they were still able to contribute to the offspring pool.

The key comparison for Pinocchio’s dolphin is whether an adult was mature and alive the year a juvenile was born. We can visualise this by directly juxtaposing the distribution of adult maturity and sampling years onto the distribution of juvenile birth years:

At this stage, we have no other information that would allow us to differentiate the probability of adult \(i\) being the parent of offspring \(j\), other than the year of sampling, the age of the adult when sampled (which gives us the year when they were mature), and the birth date of the juveniles. Therefore, we can aggregate our adults according to those variables and make comparisons across the resulting strata, instead of making pairwise comparisons between each adult and juvenile samples. This is more efficient than looping through 2.2407975^{7} pairwise comparisons (i.e. the number of adults \(\times\) the number of juveniles).

So, we want to compute the probability that a female of age \(A\) sampled in year \(Y\) is the mother of a juvenile of birth year \(B\), given the number of juveniles produced in year \(B\).

The tutorial code implements this in two steps. First, prior to defining and fitting the models, quantities are computed by the function boring_data_prep_delfi_A which returns an environment object:

# use code from 'generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal' to define likelihood
lglk_delfi_A <- generic_lglk_MOP_ideal_mammal 
env <- boring_data_prep_delfi_A(samp_delfi_A, prev_env=environment(lglk_delfi_A))

As the model itself is defined in lglk_delfi_A, we assign env as the environment of lglk_delfi_A, which makes the objects defined in env accessible to the code executed within lglk_delfi_A. The main advantage of doing this is that preliminary computations do not have to be provided as additional arguments to the lglk_delfi_A function, or redone from scratch for every model iteration. See here for a more in-depth explanation on how environments work in R.

One of two key quantities computed by boring_data_prep_delfi_A is the number of possible pairwise comparisons between adults and juveniles by \(Y\)-\(A\) \(\times\) \(B\) strata. Here, comparisons are only deemed possible if the adults in \(Y\)-\(A\) were born before the juveniles born in year \(B\). The number of possible comparisons is then the product of the number of adults in the \(Y\)-\(A\) stratum and the number of juveniles born in year \(B\) (i.e. \(B > Y - A\)).

The number of pairwise comparisons by \(Y\)-\(A\) \(\times\) \(B\) strata are stored in object env$n_comp_MOP:

Code 
parentcntsmat <-  samp_delfi_A$Samps %>% filter(poss_par) %>%
    mutate(M=B+agemat) %>% group_by(Y, M) %>% tally() %>% mutate(lab='Maturity')

xl <- range(c(parentcntsmat$M, offsprcnts$B)) + c(-0.5, 0.5)

draw_comp_panel <- function(wsy=25, wcomp='All') { # which sampling year

    # get adults stats and counts for wsy
    oadf <- bind_rows(filter(parentcntsmat,  Y == wsy) %>%
                      mutate(Type = 'Adults', X = M),
                      mutate(offsprcnts, X = B, Type = 'Juveniles')) %>%
        mutate(Type=factor(Type, levels=c('Juveniles', 'Adults'), ordered=TRUE))

    # get plausible parent-offspring matches
    get_compdf <- function(wm) {
        ## to match boring_data_prep_delfi_A,
        ## only retain comparisons where adults were born >= juveniles birth year
        ## cf. n_comp_MOP
        oo <- offsprcnts %>%
            mutate(M=wm, Y=wsy) %>%
            # define types of pairwise comps
            mutate(All=TRUE,
                   Boring = B >= (M-5) & B <= Y,  # adults alive and born
                   Comp = B >= M & B <= Y) %>%  # adults alive and mature
            mutate(X=M) %>%
            filter((M-5) < B) %>% # filter out adults born after juveniles
            left_join(dplyr::select(filter(oadf, Type == 'Adults'), -B),
                      by=c('X', 'M', 'Y')) 
    }

    compdf <- lapply(oadf$M, get_compdf) %>% bind_rows
    #    numc <- sum(with(filter(compdf, (Y - M - 5) < B), n.x * n.y), na.rm=TRUE)
    numc <- sum(with(filter(compdf, .data[[wcomp]]), n.x * n.y), na.rm=TRUE)    
    labs <- c('All'='All possible pairwise comparisons:',
              'Boring'='Only pairwise comparisons where adults were *born*\nand still alive on juvenile birth year:',
              'Comp'='Only pairwise comparisons where adults were *mature*\nand still alive on juvenile birth year:')
    
    gg0 <- ggplot(oadf, aes(X, Type, fill=n)) +
        geom_tile(show.legend=FALSE) +
       scale_fill_gradientn(colours=rev(heat_hcl(40))) +
       geom_segment(data=filter(compdf, .data[[wcomp]]), aes(x=M, xend=B, y='Adults', yend='Juveniles', fill=NULL),
                    alpha=0.25, show.legend=FALSE, colour='royalblue3') +
       geom_text(aes(label=n), fontface=2, size=3) +
       annotate('text', x=Inf, y=Inf, label=paste('n =', numc), vjust=1.1, hjust=1) +
       xlab('') + ylab('') +
       xlim(xl) + ggtitle(labs[wcomp])

    #if(wsy%%2==0) gg0 <- gg0 + theme(axis.text.y=element_blank())

    gg0
}

lapply(c('All', 'Boring', 'Comp'), draw_comp_panel, wsy=27) %>%
    wrap_plots(ncol=1) +
    xlab('\nAdult maturity year vs. juvenile birth year') +
    theme(axis.title.x=element_text(hjust=-2.25))

The grey lines show all possible comparisons and the blue lines show the ones that are deemed possible. The number in the top-right corner is the total possible number of pairwise comparisons in the sampling year. You can verify that it matches those in env$n_comp_MOP, and also examine individual counts by querying cells within the offarray object, e.g.:

env$n_comp_MOP[22, 25, 12]

will show the possible number of pairwise comparisons between juveniles born in year 22 and adults sampled in year 25 of age 12.

Note that objects of class offarray are indexed based on the name of the dimensions, not the cell positions. Use dimseq(env$n_comp_MOP) to view the name of the dimensions.

Model launch

Since each Pinocchio’s dolphin female produces one offspring per year once mature, the number of recruits every year is the number of females in the population in year Y, so the probability that any recruit born in year \(B\) is the offspring of a possible parent female is \(\frac{1}{N_B}\).

The probability that a POP is detected in year Y for any females of age A and juveniles born in year B is thus:

  • the number of pairwise combinations for that age-year strata \(\times\)
  • the probability that the age-year strata can be the parent of a juvenile born in year \(B\) (i.e. Pr(female was alive in year \(B\)) [0/1] \(\times\) Pr(female was mature in year \(B\)) [0/1]) \(\times\)
  • the inverse of the number of offspring produced in year B (\(\frac{1}{N_B}\)).

We need a model that computes the likelihood of detecting 561 POPs given the distribution of our 9600 samples (observed), population size \(N\) (estimated) and growth rate \(\lambda\) (estimated).

Now that we have prepared the data, we can launch our model. The first year of the model is the earliest birth year of juveniles sampled (e.g. “1993” if juveniles were born in 1993, 1994, and 1997—here, “21”), the last year of the model is the last year an adult was sampled (here, “30”). This range is also stored in model object env$years.

For Pinocchio’s dolphin, all we need is a simple population model with two parameters: population size \(N\) at first year and the rate of increase:

\[ N_t = N_0 e^\lambda \]

For each model iteration (i.e. a candidate set of \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\)), we compute \(N_Y\) from years 21 to 30. We then loop through each combination of \(Y\)-\(A\) and \(B\) to compute the probability that an adult of age \(A\) sampled in year \(Y\) was the parent of a juvenile born in year \(B\), i.e.:

Pr(female was alive in year \(B\)) (i.e. is \(Y >= B\)) \(\times\)

Pr(female was mature in year \(B\)) (i.e. is \(Y - A + 5 <= B\)) \(\times\)

\(\displaystyle\frac{1}{N_B}\)

From this, we can predict the number of expected parent-offspring pairs detected given the sample size in each strata.

Finally, the function lk_delfi_A outputs the (Poisson) likelihood of observing \(n_{Y, A, B}\) POPs given the expected \(n\) POPs for that stratum. The model is then optimised (with nlminb) to find the combination of \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\) that minimises that log-likelihood.

environment( lglk_delfi_A) <- env # include objects from preparation step to likelihood function environment

# test some starting values for logNad and RoI 
starto <- c( log( 100000), 0.01) 
initest <- lglk_delfi_A( starto)

# fit model:
fitto <- nlminb( starto, NEG( lglk_delfi_A))

The values of \(N_0\) and \(\lambda\) that optimise the likelihood are 1.01615^{4} and 0.0119. Let’s compare that to the true values that were used when simulating the dataset:

Nfad_y0 <- exp(fitto$par[1])
RoI <- fitto$par[2]
N_y <- Nfad_y0 * exp( RoI * (env$years - env$y0))

# get true value for female population 'F': 
tru_Nadf <- apply(samp_delfi_A@secret$N_sya['F', env$years, agemat:40], 2, sum) 

maxyplot <- max( c( tru_Nadf, N_y))
par(mai=c(1, 1, 0.5, 0))
plot( env$years, tru_Nadf, type='l', ylim=c( 0, 1.1*maxyplot),
     xlab = 'Year', ylab='Numbers\n', las=1, yaxs='i')
points( env$years, env$N, col='turquoise4', pch=16)

Not bad! There are more diagnostics and options for exploring results in fit_delphi_A.r.

A note about time span and not including adults as possible offsprings. (Possible exercise?)

Diagnostics

Diagnostics for CKMR can be tricky as there is often a very small amount of observed POPs.

This example actually contains a huge amount of POPs compared to what we would usually observe, so we can compare observed vs. expected POPs for each sampling year and juvenile birth year.
